  "prompt": "What is the heaviest weight ever lifted by a human being?",
  "response": "The heaviest weight ever lifted by a human being is a subject of some debate due to the different types of lifts and the conditions under which they were performed. However, one of the most notable records is held by **Paul Anderson**, an American weightlifter and strongman.\n\n### Paul Anderson's Backlift:\n- **Weight:** 6,270 pounds (2,844 kg)\n- **Type of Lift:** Backlift\n- **Date:** Circa 1957\n\nPaul Anderson performed this incredible feat by lifting a platform loaded with weights using his back in a semi-squat position. It's important to note that a backlift is not a standard competitive lift like the clean and jerk or the deadlift, but it remains one of the heaviest documented lifts in history.\n\n### Competitive Lifts:\nIn the realm of standard competitive lifts, the heaviest verified lifts include:\n\n#### **Deadlift:**\n- **Hafthor Bj\u00f6rnsson** (aka \"The Mountain\"):\n  - **Weight:** 1,104 pounds (501 kg)\n  - **Date:** May 2, 2020\n\nThis is the heaviest deadlift ever recorded in a sanctioned event.\n\n#### **Clean & Jerk:**\n- **Lasha Talakhadze** (Georgian weightlifter):\n  - **Weight:** 267 kg (589 pounds)\n  - **Date:** December 17, 2021\n\nThis is the heaviest clean and jerk ever performed in competition.\n\n### Summary:\nWhile Paul Anderson's backlift of 6,270 pounds remains one of the heaviest documented lifts, in standard competitive lifts, Hafthor Bj\u00f6rnsson holds the record for the heaviest deadlift at 1,104 pounds, and Lasha Talakhadze holds the record for the heaviest clean and jerk at 267 kg.",
